WEBVTT

1
00:01:58.333 --> 00:02:02.793
(Theater in Quarantine Intro Music)

2
00:02:24.937 --> 00:02:30.877
Good evening. It is November 2nd, 8:07, and this is Theatre in Quarantine,

3
00:02:31.436 --> 00:02:35.697
the digital performance lab that's been live streaming from this very East Village apartment

4
00:02:35.698 --> 00:02:42.097
since 2020 when the theaters went dark. Since then, we've continued to experiment with the

5
00:02:42.217 --> 00:02:48.136
limits of live digital performance, and we are grateful to NYU Skirball for bringing us back

6
00:02:48.137 --> 00:02:51.462
to present another Halloween production.

7
00:02:52.100 --> 00:02:56.555
Now this one is being live-streamed on CultureHub's Broadcaster Platform. 

8
00:02:56.556 --> 00:03:04.493
which has been recently developed to create as live an experience as possible for you, our remote audience.

9
00:03:05.137 --> 00:03:08.722
In the bottom left-hand corner of your screen you'll find a small arrow

10
00:03:08.723 --> 00:03:12.543
that takes you to a menu of different interactive settings. 

11
00:03:12.751 --> 00:03:17.237
There you'll find access to the chat, to reaction emojis,

12
00:03:17.572 --> 00:03:23.122
and if you prefer a more focused viewing, the option to turn off all the above. 

13
00:03:23.890 --> 00:03:29.771
In the bottom right-hand corner of your screen, you'll notice a small backstage camera view,

14
00:03:29.771 --> 00:03:34.007
which you can click anytime to toggle between streams. 

15
00:03:34.417 --> 00:03:37.606
Now one side gives you the curated performance feed,

16
00:03:37.750 --> 00:03:44.920
the version that we've rehearsed, designed, composed, and are carefully stitching together for you, live, tonight.

17
00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:51.452
The other side shows a behind the scenes camera, a static wide-shot of this apartment,

18
00:03:51.583 --> 00:03:56.326
where you'll catch all the real-time chaos that makes the illusion possible. 

19
00:03:56.667 --> 00:04:00.929
You can move between the performance and backstage at your leisure. 

20
00:04:01.303 --> 00:04:04.500
In other words, just like the phantom,

21
00:04:04.631 --> 00:04:07.425
you choose between the artifice of the opera

22
00:04:07.425 --> 00:04:10.323
and the reality of the infrastructure. 

23
00:04:10.795 --> 00:04:16.997
Now, get ready with me as I become the Phantom.

24
00:04:23.717 --> 00:04:25.296
Many people have asked me

25
00:04:25.297 --> 00:04:27.137
why we're doing another Phantom of the Opera.

26
00:04:27.977 --> 00:04:32.257
Hasn't been done? and done and done,

27
00:04:32.257 --> 00:04:37.149
done silently, done musically, done immersively?

28
00:04:38.117 --> 00:04:43.970
What could possibly be left to say about a monstrous man living beneath an opera house —

29
00:04:43.970 --> 00:04:49.177
this enormous crumbling monument to high art,

30
00:04:49.717 --> 00:04:52.057
a national museum really, a mausoleum

31
00:04:52.837 --> 00:04:56.077
for a faithful few's occasional pilgrimage.

32
00:04:57.087 --> 00:04:59.897
I mean, there used to be opera houses everywhere.

33
00:04:59.897 --> 00:05:03.777
Entire industries built around singers, designers, and artisans.

34
00:05:03.777 --> 00:05:07.912
Now, most countries, there's maybe one national company left.

35
00:05:08.757 --> 00:05:13.397
A single luxury house propped up by subsidies and nostalgia.

36
00:05:14.657 --> 00:05:20.184
Because, maybe the Phantom isn't just a man hiding under a mask.

37
00:05:21.237 --> 00:05:23.777
Maybe he's the infrastructure itself.

38
00:05:24.977 --> 00:05:29.353
Which is why in wrestling with the question of the Phantom's face,

39
00:05:29.797 --> 00:05:34.980
we think of it not as disfigurement, but as damage.

40
00:05:35.417 --> 00:05:40.377
the visible strain of keeping a collapsing system alive.

41
00:05:40.937 --> 00:05:43.337
The cracks are architectural.

42
00:05:43.337 --> 00:05:45.937
The rot, institutional.

43
00:05:45.937 --> 00:05:47.157
Budgets shrink.

44
00:05:48.777 --> 00:05:50.337
Maybe someone should blow it all up.

45
00:05:52.477 --> 00:05:57.837
It cannot and will not be a truly popular art form again.

46
00:05:58.057 --> 00:05:58.990
So what do we do?

47
00:05:59.457 --> 00:06:01.217
What do we do with the once popular?

48
00:06:01.217 --> 00:06:03.452
We entomb it in marble.

49
00:06:04.357 --> 00:06:07.380
bury it in the basement, call it preservation.

50
00:06:07.937 --> 00:06:09.675
We write dramaturgical notes.

51
00:06:09.957 --> 00:06:13.917
We flood it with luxury formaldehyde.

52
00:06:13.977 --> 00:06:17.872
We advertise this pale, taxidermied imitation.

53
00:06:18.957 --> 00:06:22.017
Have you ever seen the one about the impresario

54
00:06:22.337 --> 00:06:27.029
who drags an opera house up a mountain in the Amazon?

55
00:06:27.997 --> 00:06:30.897
It's an old showboat with a paddle wheel.

56
00:06:30.997 --> 00:06:35.149
It's very Sisyphean, very imperialist.

57
00:06:36.837 --> 00:06:40.788
Where's new music that doesn't take a higher degree to appreciate?

58
00:06:41.957 --> 00:06:43.917
All these works are in the public domain.

59
00:06:43.917 --> 00:06:48.216
Why are we beholden to their staccato marking?

60
00:06:48.216 --> 00:06:49.437
And who cares?

61
00:06:49.437 --> 00:06:53.357
Apparently the subscribers — dogmatic extremists —

62
00:06:54.557 --> 00:07:01.353
How can you possibly introduce  conventions so antiquated to a new audience?

63
00:07:02.237 --> 00:07:03.937
Music appreciation class?

64
00:07:05.177 --> 00:07:10.537
It'll happen to theater like it happened to the opera,
like it'll happen to the cinema.

65
00:07:10.897 --> 00:07:15.404
Anywhere real people congregate in real space, in real time.

66
00:07:16.977 --> 00:07:18.997
Did you know that when they built the opera house,

67
00:07:18.997 --> 00:07:20.880
they cleared an entire neighborhood,

68
00:07:21.423 --> 00:07:28.348
evicted, relocated for the sensory pleasure of the wealthy and the powerful.

69
00:07:29.227 --> 00:07:36.097
There were rumors two of the bricklayers were crushed to death when they laid the foundation.

70
00:07:36.367 --> 00:07:39.657
A real community, torn up from the roots

71
00:07:39.817 --> 00:07:46.214
so that imaginary worlds could ascend and descend in mere seconds...

72
00:07:46.214 --> 00:07:48.603
...like magic.

73
00:07:48.970 --> 00:07:51.712
They did a Moby Dick last season.

74
00:07:51.712 --> 00:07:58.917
Ahab, screeching in a bemused tenor upon a trumped up peg leg chasing the old white whale,

75
00:07:58.917 --> 00:08:02.088
thinking he's the one doing the hunting.

76
00:08:02.088 --> 00:08:06.963
Oh, captain, my captain, who will tell you it is you who are being hunted?

77
00:08:07.478 --> 00:08:12.748
(Overture begins)

78
00:12:35.377 --> 00:12:40.177
(A soprano vocalizing)

79
00:13:22.440 --> 00:13:32.417
(Metronomes ticking)

80
00:13:35.100 --> 00:13:48.568
(Soprano vocalizations)

81
00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:00.118
(Vocalizations end)

82
00:14:35.480 --> 00:14:40.511
(Phone ringing)

83
00:16:13.700 --> 00:16:14.918
Are you there?

84
00:16:17.880 --> 00:16:19.177
A Voice: "Yes."

85
00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:22.580
He doesn't deserve this.

86
00:16:22.880 --> 00:16:37.610
"You did what you had to do. You must absolve yourself of these material things."

87
00:16:37.610 --> 00:16:44.920
"For tonight, you will make the angels in heaven weep."

88
00:16:47.340 --> 00:16:51.505
Thank you, angel of music.

89
00:16:51.900 --> 00:16:55.633
(Orchestra tuning)

90
00:17:55.800 --> 00:17:57.200
(Applause)

91
00:18:01.987 --> 00:18:03.603
(Tap of  Conductor's baton)

92
00:18:04.187 --> 00:18:07.000
(Orchestra begins playing)

93
00:19:10.540 --> 00:19:11.940
(Singing in French)

94
00:19:38.283 --> 00:19:40.645
(Male baritone singing in French)

95
00:21:20.607 --> 00:21:29.607
(Applause)

96
00:25:40.062 --> 00:25:45.718
(Rehearsal piano plays)

97
00:26:14.230 --> 00:26:19.005
(Telephone ringing)

98
00:26:39.765 --> 00:26:41.165
(Violinist tuning)

99
00:33:04.587 --> 00:33:08.353
(Distorted operatic music)

100
00:34:05.966 --> 00:34:09.652
(A sharp electrical pulse halts the music)

101
00:34:15.202 --> 00:34:18.002
(Music resumes)

102
00:34:20.674 --> 00:34:24.401
(Another electrical short)

103
00:34:30.019 --> 00:34:34.949
(Music and singing resumes again)

104
00:34:40.423 --> 00:34:43.828
(An even more violent electrical surge)

105
00:34:51.481 --> 00:34:56.341
(Tinkling, clinking chandelier crystals  )

106
00:36:11.630 --> 00:36:12.825
Was that you?

107
00:36:15.740 --> 00:36:17.820
The Voice: "It was a faulty cable."

108
00:36:20.200 --> 00:36:25.340
"Management should have taken care of it years ago."

109
00:36:28.014 --> 00:36:32.821
"I'm sure the official report will say negligence."

110
00:36:34.710 --> 00:36:36.304
I didn't want this.

111
00:36:39.753 --> 00:36:41.824
"There's no need to go out there."

112
00:36:42.520 --> 00:36:43.470
But it's Raul.

113
00:36:44.353 --> 00:36:47.850
"Come to the mirror instead."

114
00:36:52.583 --> 00:36:53.962
"Close your eyes."

115
00:36:55.340 --> 00:37:02.820
"Take one step forward... and open them."

116
00:37:30.038 --> 00:37:31.507
(Door slams)

117
00:37:41.193 --> 00:37:43.049
(Splash of water)

118
00:38:32.095 --> 00:38:34.048
Think not on the mask.

119
00:38:35.873 --> 00:38:42.532
Listen to my voice. You recognize me.

120
00:38:43.596 --> 00:38:46.915
You know me.

121
00:38:49.483 --> 00:38:52.051
Angel of music...

122
00:39:57.258 --> 00:39:59.838
Are you not comfortable?

123
00:40:01.258 --> 00:40:02.353
Where am I?

124
00:40:04.478 --> 00:40:06.478
Five cellars underground.

125
00:40:09.600 --> 00:40:11.700
Are we still in the opera house?

126
00:40:12.620 --> 00:40:17.319
Below the orchestra and the dressing rooms.

127
00:40:17.319 --> 00:40:23.580
Below the trap room and that old cistern that used to run hydraulics.

128
00:40:24.740 --> 00:40:27.572
Somewhere even lower.

129
00:40:29.900 --> 00:40:33.315
I have lived in these cellars for many years.

130
00:40:33.540 --> 00:40:36.555
A nameless legend.

131
00:40:43.080 --> 00:40:45.318
You are the Phantom.

132
00:40:45.318 --> 00:40:47.198
I am many things.

133
00:40:48.510 --> 00:40:49.922
I am your teacher.

134
00:40:51.260 --> 00:40:53.510
I am your patron.

135
00:40:55.140 --> 00:41:01.315
I am your angel of music.

136
00:41:04.359 --> 00:41:07.200
You have no need to be afraid.

137
00:41:09.320 --> 00:41:10.692
Not of me.

138
00:41:13.260 --> 00:41:14.709
I want to go.

139
00:41:15.192 --> 00:41:17.872
You are not a prisoner.

140
00:41:18.780 --> 00:41:22.890
You are my masterpiece.

141
00:41:22.890 --> 00:41:25.354
(Organ music)

142
00:41:49.333 --> 00:41:52.302
(Singing in French)

143
00:42:34.187 --> 00:42:39.234
Now when I sing, I hardly recognize myself.

144
00:43:05.533 --> 00:43:08.203
How long must I stay here?

145
00:43:12.753 --> 00:43:16.328
Until you are no longer afraid of me.

146
00:43:18.020 --> 00:43:23.392
I have given you everything you have ever desired.

147
00:43:25.973 --> 00:43:28.456
What more do you want?

148
00:43:29.580 --> 00:43:31.210
Is Marguerite not enough?

149
00:43:35.253 --> 00:43:36.526
What then?

150
00:43:37.913 --> 00:43:43.382
Tosca, Violetta, Mimi, Lucia?

151
00:43:43.383 --> 00:43:44.882
I want fame.

152
00:43:46.643 --> 00:43:47.300
Why?

153
00:43:50.723 --> 00:43:52.178
I want to be perfect.

154
00:43:52.563 --> 00:43:54.283
You are perfect.

155
00:43:54.367 --> 00:43:55.277
I'm beautiful.

156
00:43:55.807 --> 00:43:57.214
You are beautiful.

157
00:43:58.093 --> 00:43:59.935
But I want to be loved.

158
00:44:00.600 --> 00:44:02.020
You are loved.

159
00:44:02.853 --> 00:44:08.683
I want to be... it's a word I don't know how to translate it.

160
00:44:10.063 --> 00:44:11.392
"Incontournable."

161
00:44:12.843 --> 00:44:14.143
It's more than love.

162
00:44:15.500 --> 00:44:19.989
I want to be part of the firmament, incontrovertible.

163
00:44:21.413 --> 00:44:25.608
I suppose I sing in order to exist.

164
00:44:26.660 --> 00:44:29.210
To belong to everyone and no one.

165
00:44:29.353 --> 00:44:32.093
You belong to me.

166
00:44:34.113 --> 00:44:36.104
So let me see your face.

167
00:44:36.105 --> 00:44:38.225
Do not touch the mask!

168
00:44:38.663 --> 00:44:39.863
This is not a request.

169
00:44:41.097 --> 00:44:42.917
This is a warning.

170
00:44:42.917 --> 00:44:45.524
It is the only rule.

171
00:44:46.913 --> 00:44:50.993
Can you bear to love me

172
00:44:53.773 --> 00:44:58.033
with this one small inconvenience?

173
00:44:58.353 --> 00:45:01.253
(Metronome ticking)

174
00:45:16.483 --> 00:45:19.483
Christine's voice: My father was the finest violinist in the world.

175
00:45:20.583 --> 00:45:24.570
He claimed that all great musicians, once in their lives,

176
00:45:24.570 --> 00:45:27.322
receive a visit from the angel of music.

177
00:45:28.763 --> 00:45:31.570
And you will hear him too, my child.

178
00:45:32.790 --> 00:45:36.342
When I am in heaven, I will send him to you.

179
00:45:37.965 --> 00:45:43.062
When you first spoke to me, I thought I was going mad.

180
00:45:44.163 --> 00:45:47.285
I thought you came from heaven.

181
00:45:48.598 --> 00:45:50.394
(Organ music)

182
00:46:16.713 --> 00:46:20.311
"Don Juan Triumphant." I don't know it.

183
00:46:21.730 --> 00:46:23.992
I compose sometimes.

184
00:46:26.124 --> 00:46:31.191
I have been working on this piece for some time.

185
00:46:32.773 --> 00:46:37.253
I was once afraid that I would never finish it.

186
00:46:38.713 --> 00:46:46.520
Now, I am afraid what will happen when I do.

187
00:46:48.201 --> 00:46:49.964
You will never hear it.

188
00:46:51.133 --> 00:46:56.472
My Don Juan is so horrifying...

189
00:46:57.323 --> 00:47:01.473
...it consumes all those who come near it.

190
00:47:04.713 --> 00:47:05.836
Come, Christine.

191
00:47:06.226 --> 00:47:10.461
Let us sing Mozart instead.

192
00:47:14.473 --> 00:47:16.453
(Singing "Don Giovanni")

193
00:49:18.273 --> 00:49:19.793
How do you like it?!

194
00:49:20.833 --> 00:49:24.453
I'm handsome, aren't I?!

195
00:49:25.333 --> 00:49:28.613
Like your lover, aren't I?!

196
00:49:29.213 --> 00:49:36.373
I thought that if you believed me to be beautiful...

197
00:49:36.373 --> 00:49:41.293
that I might know...

198
00:49:45.133 --> 00:49:51.982
I was going to give you everything you ever wanted.

199
00:49:52.413 --> 00:49:58.071
All you had to do was not touch the mask!

200
00:50:29.893 --> 00:50:34.253
I will show you the depth of my love.

201
00:50:37.233 --> 00:50:42.567
I will let you go...

202
00:50:43.813 --> 00:50:47.050
...back up and sing.

203
00:50:48.953 --> 00:50:53.727
So long as you never see your lover again.

204
00:50:54.893 --> 00:51:00.373
If you do, it is death to you both.

205
00:53:49.913 --> 00:53:51.973
For the past three months,

206
00:53:51.973 --> 00:53:54.753
the angel of music has been coming to my dressing room

207
00:53:54.753 --> 00:53:56.342
to give me lessons.

208
00:53:58.993 --> 00:54:01.202
That voice you heard, remember?

209
00:54:03.933 --> 00:54:05.695
It was no angel, Raoul.

210
00:54:07.433 --> 00:54:08.631
It was the Phantom.

211
00:54:09.593 --> 00:54:11.350
He's no ghost and I've seen him.

212
00:54:12.253 --> 00:54:15.033
I figured if I was talking to you,

213
00:54:15.033 --> 00:54:17.980
he'd take me back to that lake underground.

214
00:54:21.913 --> 00:54:24.968
It doesn't make sense when I try to remember.

215
00:54:26.423 --> 00:54:29.978
I was so drawn to him, to his voice.

216
00:54:31.593 --> 00:54:34.253
But it was his face I wanted to see.

217
00:58:16.073 --> 00:58:19.565
You thought that you could leave the opera,

218
00:58:20.093 --> 00:58:22.680
that you could run away from me,

219
00:58:23.293 --> 00:58:25.253
The one who made you great.

220
00:58:28.673 --> 00:58:32.383
Sounds like the gala performance is starting

221
00:58:32.383 --> 00:58:34.453
without its new prima donna.

222
00:58:35.033 --> 00:58:36.913
You see how disposable you are.

223
00:58:37.913 --> 00:58:42.333
All of you are so easily replaced.

224
00:58:43.413 --> 00:58:48.113
The artists, the patrons,

225
00:58:49.333 --> 00:58:56.793
Even the donors will all die out and be replaced by a younger generation...

226
00:58:59.053 --> 00:59:00.821
But not me.

227
00:59:02.313 --> 00:59:06.233
I am the opera.

228
00:59:07.313 --> 00:59:10.103
I am the institution.

229
00:59:10.893 --> 00:59:13.410
And I could never forget you.

230
00:59:14.115 --> 00:59:16.655
Not if I lived a thousand years.

231
00:59:17.333 --> 00:59:22.511
If you could love me, Christine, we would become one.

232
00:59:23.003 --> 00:59:25.436
And you would become...

233
00:59:26.593 --> 00:59:29.578
part of the opera forever.

234
00:59:30.769 --> 00:59:32.664
Incontrovertible.

235
00:59:34.193 --> 00:59:38.018
Part of the firmament.

236
00:59:44.333 --> 00:59:50.113
If you'd have me, Christine, I would write you the grandest operas to sing.

237
00:59:50.113 --> 00:59:51.871
Not just Faust.

238
00:59:52.613 --> 00:59:54.093
Not just Aida.

239
00:59:54.093 --> 00:59:55.970
Aida, Aida.

240
00:59:55.970 --> 01:00:02.313
Aida must have her Radames — sealed in a tomb, singing their last breath.

241
01:00:02.313 --> 01:00:04.293
That's the choice she made.

242
01:00:04.773 --> 01:00:10.225
To live a princess, or die buried underground.

243
01:00:10.453 --> 01:00:13.692
And now you too have a choice to make, Christine.

244
01:00:14.393 --> 01:00:18.833
The wedding mass or the requiem mass?

245
01:00:19.373 --> 01:00:24.081
If you choose the wedding mass, we shall be married.

246
01:00:24.081 --> 01:00:27.633
And I will do anything to ensure my wife

247
01:00:27.733 --> 01:00:30.392
gets everything she ever wanted.

248
01:00:31.133 --> 01:00:35.373
If you choose the requiem mass, then boom,

249
01:00:35.373 --> 01:00:38.273
you, me, your lover, the opera house.

250
01:00:40.253 --> 01:00:42.542
blown to a million bits.

251
01:00:43.573 --> 01:00:47.073
Over the years I've buried enough explosives down here

252
01:00:47.073 --> 01:00:49.827
to blow up a quarter of the city.

253
01:00:53.293 --> 01:00:56.793
I had thought to play my requiem many times

254
01:00:56.793 --> 01:00:58.833
before you, Christine.

255
01:00:59.473 --> 01:01:03.556
Sitting in this damp shadow of a life.

256
01:01:04.793 --> 01:01:07.452
I'd been planning to take all of those

257
01:01:07.453 --> 01:01:12.013
jewel bedecked shoulders to the grave with me for a long time.

258
01:01:13.653 --> 01:01:15.613
And then I heard your voice.

259
01:01:16.933 --> 01:01:20.602
And for the first time in my life I felt hope.

260
01:01:21.513 --> 01:01:23.513
Hope that I might be loved.

261
01:01:25.053 --> 01:01:28.833
That I might create something beautiful to leave behind.

262
01:01:30.253 --> 01:01:34.937
Hope that opera could matter again.

263
01:01:38.393 --> 01:01:42.202
Do you think you could love me, Christine?

264
01:01:43.273 --> 01:01:48.233
I know that together we could make you immortal.

265
01:01:48.233 --> 01:01:57.472
But without you, without your voice, I may as well take it all down with me.

266
01:02:00.793 --> 01:02:02.923
But you must make a choice.

267
01:02:03.713 --> 01:02:08.093
Unless I stop it, the explosives are set to blow

268
01:02:08.093 --> 01:02:11.488
on the final note of tonight's opening act.

269
01:02:11.773 --> 01:02:15.713
I fear you have but moments to choose.

270
01:02:15.713 --> 01:02:18.533
Wedding mass or requiem mass?

271
01:02:18.533 --> 01:02:21.192
Immortality or obsolescence?

272
01:02:24.133 --> 01:02:29.480
Do you wish to one day leave behind a legacy of greatness...

273
01:02:30.154 --> 01:02:42.678
...or to be burnt to ashes, carried off by the wind, and forgotten by the hands of time.

274
01:03:40.361 --> 01:03:49.923
(Opera music)

275
01:03:54.513 --> 01:04:14.146
(Applause)

